<Link id="l00027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="27"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This class provides support for dynamic arbitrary-precision arithmetic.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="28"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="29"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Unlike APInt, this extends the precision as necessary to prevent overflows</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="30"><Highlight kind="comment">/// and supports operations between objects with differing internal precisions.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="31"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="32"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This is optimized for small-values by providing fast-paths for the cases</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="33"><Highlight kind="comment">/// when the value stored fits in 64-bits. We annotate all fastpaths by using</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="34"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the LLVM&#95;LIKELY/LLVM&#95;UNLIKELY annotations. Removing these would result in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="35"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a 1.2x performance slowdown.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="36"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="37"><Highlight kind="comment">/// We always&#95;inline all operations; removing these results in a 1.5x</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="38"><Highlight kind="comment">/// performance slowdown.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="39"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00040" /><CodeLine lineNumber="40"><Highlight kind="comment">/// When isLarge returns true, a SlowMPInt is held in the union. If isSmall</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00041" /><CodeLine lineNumber="41"><Highlight kind="comment">/// returns true, the int64&#95;t is held. We don&#39;t have a separate field for</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00042" /><CodeLine lineNumber="42"><Highlight kind="comment">/// indicating this, and instead &quot;steal&quot; memory from ValLarge when it is not in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00043" /><CodeLine lineNumber="43"><Highlight kind="comment">/// use because we know that the memory layout of APInt is such that BitWidth</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00044" /><CodeLine lineNumber="44"><Highlight kind="comment">/// doesn&#39;t overlap with ValSmall (see static&#95;assert&#95;layout). Using std::variant</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00045" /><CodeLine lineNumber="45"><Highlight kind="comment">/// instead would lead to significantly worse performance.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
